The paper deals with the complexity of non-commutative computation, specifically the non-commutative determinant and permanent. This falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper also involves the use of graphs and adjacency matrices, which are common topics in algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) and computational geometry (cs.CG). The lower bound results on branching programs suggest a connection to computational game theory (cs.GT) and logic in computer science (cs.LO).
